    body: "The Lord's Prayer (Pater Noster) occupies a privileged place in the Communion rite, serving as the immediate preparation for reception of the Eucharist. Its position is profoundly logical: the petition 'Give us this day our daily bread' has been interpreted since the Church Fathers (Tertullian, Cyprian, Augustine) as referring not only to material bread but to the Eucharistic Bread. The embolism that follows ('Deliver us, Lord, we pray, from every evil…') expands the final petition of the Our Father. In the Ordinary Form, the assembly prays it together; in the Extraordinary Form, only the priest recites it aloud, with the congregation responding with the final petition. The doxology 'For the kingdom, the power, and the glory are yours' was added in the post-conciliar reform.",
